    <subexercises>
      <title>Challenge</title>
      <exercise>
        <webwork>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Line <m>S</m> has the equation <m>y = ax + b</m> and Line <m>T</m> has the equation
              <m>y = cx + d</m>. Suppose <m>a\gt b\gt c\gt d\gt 0</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              <ol marker="a.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What can you say about Line <m>S</m> and Line <m>T</m>, given that <m>a\gt c</m>?
                    Give as much information about Line <m>S</m> and Line <m>T</m> as possible.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <var form="essay"/>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What can you say about Line <m>S</m> and Line <m>T</m>, given that <m>b\gt d</m>?
                    Give as much information about Line <m>S</m> and Line <m>T</m> as possible.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <var form="essay"/>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <ol marker="a.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Since Line <m>S</m> has the equation <m>y = ax + b</m> and Line <m>T</m> has the
                    equation <m>y =cx + d</m>, the variables <m>a</m> and <m>c</m> represent slopes.
                    Since <m> a \gt c \gt 0</m>, we know that the slope of Line <m>S</m> is steeper
                    than the slope of Line <m>T</m>. We also know that both slopes are positive.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Since Line <m>S</m> has the equation <m>y = ax + b</m> and Line <m>T</m> has the
                    equation <m>y =cx + d</m>, the variables <m>b</m> and <m>b</m> represent
                    <m>y</m>-intercepts. Since <m>b \gt d \gt 0</m>, we know that Line <m>S</m> and
                    Line <m>T</m> both intersect the <m>y</m>-axis at positive <m>y</m>-intercepts
                    and that Line <m>S</m> intersects the <m>y</m>-axis at a higher point than Line
                    <m>T</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
      </exercise> 
    </subexercises>
